WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.840
I'd really like to welcome our first keynote speakers, Mine Çetinkaya-Rundel and Julia

00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:15.720
Lowndes, who are going to be talking about Quarto.

00:00:15.720 --> 00:00:22.280
And there are literally no two better people suited to give this talk.

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:25.600
Mine is my colleague at rstudio.

00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:29.559
She's also my co-author of Alpha Data Science.

00:00:29.559 --> 00:00:35.520
She is a professor of the practice at Duke and just a fantastic educator.

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:40.680
And I deeply appreciate her empathy with new r users.

00:00:40.680 --> 00:00:45.680
Also whenever I correctly type Mine's full name, including the little dangly sedilla

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:52.080
on the C, I like give myself a self high five.

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:57.500
Julia Lowndes did a PhD in marine biology and squids.

00:00:57.500 --> 00:01:04.580
She also started Openscapes in 2018, supported by Mozilla.

00:01:04.580 --> 00:01:09.379
Julia is like one of the people I just love to hang out with at rstudio conf.

00:01:09.379 --> 00:01:15.620
Whenever I see her, because she is just so passionate about educating people about the

00:01:15.620 --> 00:01:21.139
power of R. And whenever I get to hang out with her, I just feel rejuvenated and excited

00:01:21.139 --> 00:01:23.099
about the work that I do.

00:01:23.099 --> 00:01:26.900
Unfortunately, Julia and Mine will not be taking answering questions today.

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:30.680
But if you do ask questions in the Slido, they will read them and they will pass them

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:33.260
on to the Cordo team.

00:01:33.260 --> 00:01:35.900
But they will not be taking questions today.

00:01:35.900 --> 00:01:50.099
So please join me in welcoming Julia and Mine.

00:01:50.099 --> 00:01:51.559
Thanks so much, Hadley.

00:01:51.559 --> 00:01:53.419
And thanks so much to all of you.

00:01:53.419 --> 00:01:56.459
We are so excited to be here.

00:01:56.459 --> 00:01:59.660
Mina and I have been using Quarto for over a year now.

00:01:59.660 --> 00:02:04.180
Mina has been teaching with it and has been contributing to the development of it.

00:02:04.180 --> 00:02:09.059
And my teams with Openscapes were the first external testers of Quarto.

00:02:09.059 --> 00:02:13.820
And as we've used it over the past year, we have grown to love it so much, and we are

00:02:13.820 --> 00:02:17.699
excited to welcome you to Quarto.

00:02:17.699 --> 00:02:20.580
But also, we know you have questions.

00:02:20.580 --> 00:02:22.059
We did, too.

00:02:22.059 --> 00:02:23.460
What is Quarto?

00:02:23.460 --> 00:02:25.100
Why is Quarto?

00:02:25.100 --> 00:02:30.660
And how does it interoperate with R Markdown and your other existing workflows?

00:02:30.660 --> 00:02:37.100
Well, Quarto unifies and extends the R Markdown ecosystem.

00:02:37.100 --> 00:02:43.339
It unifies it for people who love R Markdown so that little points of friction are reduced

00:02:43.339 --> 00:02:46.660
as you make websites and books and slides.

00:02:46.660 --> 00:02:49.500
All of those will now have a common approach.

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:55.740
And it extends it for people who do not yet know R Markdown as a friendly way to work

00:02:55.740 --> 00:03:04.059
reproducibly and publish documents that combine text and code and output in the same place.

00:03:04.059 --> 00:03:10.639
So Quarto is a new open source scientific and technical publishing system.

00:03:10.639 --> 00:03:18.100
And the goal is to make the process of creating and collaborating dramatically better.

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:25.259
So it handles inputs in multiple languages and outputs in multiple formats, all going

00:03:25.259 --> 00:03:29.179
through the same Quarto machinery.

00:03:29.179 --> 00:03:35.220
So in our talk today, we'll introduce you to Quarto through stories and demos.

00:03:35.220 --> 00:03:41.820
First, Mina will focus on how Quarto unifies the R Markdown ecosystem through stories of

00:03:41.820 --> 00:03:44.639
sharing and teaching.

00:03:44.639 --> 00:03:50.320
And then I'll focus on how Quarto extends the R Markdown ecosystem through collaborating

00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:52.919
and reimagining.

00:03:52.919 --> 00:03:55.360
So we are so excited to get started.

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:59.720
So let's kick it off with you, Mina, to talk about sharing with Quarto.

00:03:59.720 --> 00:04:01.160
Thanks, Julie.

00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:05.240
I'm so excited to have the opportunity to talk to you about Quarto, which I've been

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:08.360
living and breathing over the last year.

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:13.119
So I work at the intersection of education, research, and development.

00:04:13.119 --> 00:04:18.559
The word educator might make you think that I am in front of crowds like this, maybe smaller,

00:04:18.559 --> 00:04:21.200
24-7 lecturing at them.

00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:26.640
But actually, I spend a lot of my time in front of my computer creating and authoring

00:04:26.640 --> 00:04:31.119
artifacts that I share with the world for the purpose of teaching.

00:04:31.119 --> 00:04:37.239
And I often think everything I create, I share openly with an open license that allows for

00:04:37.239 --> 00:04:42.079
use, reuse, and adaptation.

00:04:42.079 --> 00:04:48.320
I often think web first for wider reach, but I also still live in the confines of academia

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:53.720
and traditional publishing, which means that I still have to make a lot of PDFs.

00:04:53.720 --> 00:05:00.799
Therefore, an authoring system that allows me to achieve multiple outputs from the same

00:05:00.799 --> 00:05:08.799
input, the same source code, that brings code and prose together is not only essential for

00:05:08.799 --> 00:05:15.799
me, but it's actually basically what I need to carry on my existence.

00:05:15.799 --> 00:05:20.320
And for the last decade, that has been our markdown for me.

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:27.920
In fact, I remember very vividly when JJ and Yue gave a talk at USAR 2012, the first USAR

00:05:27.920 --> 00:05:31.480
I attended, on Knitter.

00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:35.839
So I'll kind of go back to that time.

00:05:35.839 --> 00:05:39.679
When I attended that conference, I don't think I would have identified myself as an

00:05:39.679 --> 00:05:40.679
R person.

00:05:40.679 --> 00:05:44.619
In fact, I'm pretty sure we went to that conference because we were going to Bonnaroo already

00:05:44.619 --> 00:05:47.519
and it was there, and I thought, why not?

00:05:47.519 --> 00:05:52.000
This was the summer of my first year of teaching at Duke.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:55.040
I was very dedicated to open science.

00:05:55.040 --> 00:06:02.239
I had already been working on an open source textbook, but this idea of kind of wider reach

00:06:02.239 --> 00:06:07.559
and open science, but also doing computing, I had not really put the pieces together.

00:06:07.559 --> 00:06:11.239
And one of the reasons why I had not put those pieces together is that I didn't have a good

00:06:11.239 --> 00:06:13.920
workflow to bring them together.

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:20.839
If you know me, you know that I'm a prolific sharer, and I like things to look pretty as

00:06:20.839 --> 00:06:25.279
well, not just be functional and pretty, and I really did not have a good workflow for

00:06:25.279 --> 00:06:27.459
being able to achieve that.

00:06:27.459 --> 00:06:31.839
But I started listening to this keynote on Knitter, and it must have been no more than

00:06:31.839 --> 00:06:35.640
three slides into it that I just actually pulled out my laptop and started converting

00:06:35.640 --> 00:06:41.160
my teaching materials to use it, because this idea that I can bring narrative and then code

00:06:41.160 --> 00:06:47.160
together and have it just be like syntax highlighted and look organized and be ready to be published

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:51.359
on the web was just such a dream come true for me.

00:06:51.359 --> 00:06:57.480
And by the end of that keynote, I was already brainstorming ways of not just me using it,

00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:01.299
but thinking about how can I teach this to my intro students?

00:07:01.299 --> 00:07:04.739
So I am going to call this keynote a success.

00:07:04.739 --> 00:07:11.619
If some of you have already tuned me out, took out your laptops and have gone to Corto.org

00:07:11.619 --> 00:07:15.059
to start playing with it.

00:07:15.059 --> 00:07:21.660
But I do hope that you will continue to listen with one ear and take in these beautiful illustrations

00:07:21.660 --> 00:07:23.540
by Alice and Horst.

00:07:23.540 --> 00:07:29.299
And for those of you who want kind of a more laid-back morning, you can go to this link,

00:07:29.299 --> 00:07:37.859
nina.corto.pub, sit back, and I will advance the slides for you.

00:07:37.859 --> 00:07:44.239
So Julie mentioned that about unifying the R Markdown ecosystem.

00:07:44.239 --> 00:07:46.859
So let's dig into that a little bit more.

00:07:46.859 --> 00:07:54.339
Here are some of the packages from the R Markdown ecosystem that you've come to love and rely

00:07:54.339 --> 00:07:56.260
on over the years.

00:07:56.260 --> 00:08:00.660
Each package addresses a different need and solves a different problem.

00:08:00.660 --> 00:08:06.459
You might be creating websites or writing blogs with blog down or distill, writing books

00:08:06.459 --> 00:08:12.100
with book down, writing journal articles with articles package.

00:08:12.100 --> 00:08:16.220
Corto unifies the functionality of these packages.

00:08:16.220 --> 00:08:19.380
On the technical side, building on Pandoc.

00:08:19.380 --> 00:08:26.779
And on the human side, building on over a decade of experience developing, maintaining,

00:08:26.779 --> 00:08:34.979
and tweaking these packages, as well as community feedback and the extension packages developed

00:08:34.979 --> 00:08:37.099
by the community.

00:08:37.099 --> 00:08:43.580
And such a unification process presents a really nice opportunity to identify and address

00:08:43.580 --> 00:08:48.380
gaps in functionality and inefficiencies in user experience.

00:08:48.380 --> 00:08:51.780
And developing Corto has been no different.

00:08:51.780 --> 00:08:57.460
So some highlights of these improvements that are near and dear to my heart are a consistent

00:08:57.460 --> 00:09:01.780
implementation of attractive and handy features across outputs.

00:09:01.780 --> 00:09:05.619
So tab sets, code folding, syntax highlighting.

00:09:05.619 --> 00:09:10.940
Imagine these things just working out of the box regardless of what you're producing.

00:09:10.940 --> 00:09:17.900
Also more accessible defaults, as well as better support for creating accessible documents.

00:09:18.700 --> 00:09:21.659
That are particularly helpful for new learners.

00:09:21.659 --> 00:09:26.340
Things like YAML completion and informative syntax errors.

00:09:26.340 --> 00:09:30.940
And perhaps excitingly for those of you who are not coming to this from the R Markdown

00:09:30.940 --> 00:09:37.179
ecosystem, support for other languages like Python, Julia, observable, via the Jupyter

00:09:37.179 --> 00:09:41.179
engine for executable code chunks.

00:09:41.179 --> 00:09:45.619
So by now, I'm assuming you've already started playing with Corto or you're just waiting

00:09:45.619 --> 00:09:47.059
for me to do that.

00:09:47.059 --> 00:09:51.460
So let's dive in and take a look at what all the Corto fuss is about.

00:09:51.460 --> 00:09:55.140
So here I have something that might look familiar.

00:09:55.140 --> 00:09:56.140
An R Markdown document.

00:09:56.140 --> 00:10:00.140
Let's try this one more time.

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:08.340
An R Markdown document that has some YAML on top, some text, and some code.

00:10:08.340 --> 00:10:10.140
Many of you have seen this before.

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:11.140
Let's knit this document.

00:10:11.140 --> 00:10:18.380
It's a very, very simple analysis using the Palmer Penguins dataset that has a nice visualization

00:10:18.380 --> 00:10:19.940
at the bottom.

00:10:19.940 --> 00:10:24.419
So what I'm going to do first is switch over to the visual editor.

00:10:24.419 --> 00:10:27.739
I personally really like writing in the visual editor.

00:10:27.739 --> 00:10:33.419
It allows you to do things like you can bold things and italicize things without having

00:10:33.419 --> 00:10:35.539
to write Markdown code.

00:10:35.539 --> 00:10:40.099
And Julie will do a demo of the visual editor a bit more later.

00:10:40.099 --> 00:10:43.979
But I'd like to show that whether you're using the visual or the source editor with

00:10:43.979 --> 00:10:46.659
R Markdown, the output looks exactly the same.

00:10:46.659 --> 00:10:51.900
So it's just about your personal preference about authoring on the input side.

00:10:51.900 --> 00:10:54.500
But what we're going to do next is actually change things up.

00:10:54.500 --> 00:10:55.780
Let's close up that file.

00:10:55.780 --> 00:11:02.419
And what I'm going to do is just rename that RMD to be a QMD and not touch anything else.

00:11:02.419 --> 00:11:03.780
The little logo changes.

00:11:03.780 --> 00:11:04.780
I open it up.

00:11:04.780 --> 00:11:08.979
And what I have is a render button instead of a knit button.

00:11:08.979 --> 00:11:11.659
And I can see that the document just works.

00:11:11.659 --> 00:11:14.979
So Corto is able to render our Markdown documents.

00:11:14.979 --> 00:11:17.020
The output looks a little bit different.

00:11:17.020 --> 00:11:19.719
Slightly different styling.

00:11:19.719 --> 00:11:21.859
But we haven't changed anything else.

00:11:21.859 --> 00:11:27.979
We're going to change the YAML now to include the format field instead of output, which

00:11:27.979 --> 00:11:29.900
is how we define different format types.

00:11:29.900 --> 00:11:35.020
I'm going to click on render and save so that I don't have to click render every time I

00:11:35.020 --> 00:11:36.500
make changes.

00:11:36.500 --> 00:11:40.500
So again, this is basically our starting place with Corto.

00:11:40.500 --> 00:11:42.260
I can do different output formats.

00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:44.940
So let's create a PDF.

00:11:44.940 --> 00:11:50.460
One of the things I really like about creating PDFs with Corto, as a person who doesn't like

00:11:50.460 --> 00:11:56.380
creating PDFs, is that the PDF appears in the viewer as opposed to in a popup window.

00:11:56.380 --> 00:12:01.979
But let's go back to HTML and take a look at some of these chunk options.

00:12:01.979 --> 00:12:06.700
So with Corto, we're using the hash pipe for defining our chunk options, which I think

00:12:06.700 --> 00:12:09.380
helps with readability a lot.

00:12:09.380 --> 00:12:12.659
And we have really nice completion for YAML.

00:12:12.659 --> 00:12:18.580
So if I can't figure out what was that chunk option for hiding my chunks, oh, eco, how

00:12:18.580 --> 00:12:30.260
would I define the values, true or false, I can rely on the YAML completion to do that.

00:12:30.260 --> 00:12:35.940
And now on the output, we don't have that code chunk appearing anymore.

00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:42.219
I can also set global chunks, and maybe like me, this is one of your most Googled things.

00:12:42.219 --> 00:12:44.419
How do I set global chunks in Knitter?

00:12:44.419 --> 00:12:48.979
I can actually just do that now in the YAML through the execute field.

00:12:48.979 --> 00:12:55.820
So I can turn off the display of code chunks for the entire document very explicitly at

00:12:55.820 --> 00:12:58.820
the top.

00:12:58.820 --> 00:13:01.260
And now they're all gone.

00:13:01.260 --> 00:13:10.020
Well, we've been working with an HTML document, which is going to produce web-ready output.

00:13:10.020 --> 00:13:12.099
Let's take a look at one more thing.

00:13:12.099 --> 00:13:17.340
One of the reasons why I like these chunk options as hash pipes is when you have really

00:13:17.340 --> 00:13:24.340
long chunk options, say if I want to insert this lengthy text as alternative text for

00:13:24.340 --> 00:13:30.539
the plot that I am producing, it stays very kind of legible, and obviously the alternative

00:13:30.539 --> 00:13:35.260
text is not going to be visible in the output, but if I was to inspect that element, I can

00:13:35.260 --> 00:13:41.539
see that text is in the HTML source code, so that is still accessible to screen readers.

00:13:41.539 --> 00:13:47.219
Making these things easier is going to make more folks write alternative text, I think,

00:13:47.219 --> 00:13:50.659
for the visualizations that they're producing.

00:13:50.659 --> 00:13:53.140
Let's make a presentation.

00:13:53.140 --> 00:13:55.179
I don't need to touch the rest of my code.

00:13:55.179 --> 00:14:03.979
I am just going to change my YAML header to format reveal.js and create a reveal.js presentation.

00:14:03.979 --> 00:14:11.099
My title page is basically whatever was in the YAML of my document, and you can see that

00:14:11.099 --> 00:14:13.419
each of the section headers are now new slides.

00:14:13.419 --> 00:14:18.739
I have that really squished plot, because reveal.js tries to help me by making my plots

00:14:18.739 --> 00:14:25.619
take just as much space as there is, but I can easily insert another header, a second-level

00:14:25.619 --> 00:14:34.979
header to just move that content to the next slide.

00:14:34.979 --> 00:14:39.780
And to me, being able to do this without touching the rest of the content is really, really

00:14:39.780 --> 00:14:41.780
satisfying.

00:14:41.780 --> 00:14:47.179
All right.

00:14:47.179 --> 00:14:53.380
So let's go back to HTML, and next what we're going to do is attempt to make a website in

00:14:53.380 --> 00:14:55.179
less than ten minutes.

00:14:55.179 --> 00:14:58.419
So I have a single HTML document here.

00:14:58.419 --> 00:15:03.979
I'm going to create one more document, so we're basically expanding from a single document

00:15:03.979 --> 00:15:10.940
to bringing multiple documents together in a Korto project.

00:15:10.940 --> 00:15:14.219
I'm going to keep this document very simple intentionally.

00:15:14.219 --> 00:15:15.500
No computing in there.

00:15:15.500 --> 00:15:20.580
I'm just going to put a little bit of text, so I've titled my document welcome, and maybe

00:15:20.580 --> 00:15:27.140
let's add some plain text like this is the demo site for the talk.

00:15:27.140 --> 00:15:32.580
Next to bring them together, I'm going to create a YAML file, a Korto.yaml file, and

00:15:32.580 --> 00:15:37.859
I am going to write YAML on the fly, and I can do that relying on the tab completion

00:15:37.859 --> 00:15:38.859
again.

00:15:38.859 --> 00:15:41.739
So we're creating a Korto project.

00:15:41.739 --> 00:15:46.099
There are various types of Korto projects you can create.

00:15:46.099 --> 00:15:52.059
The type I'm going to select here is website, and then I am going to define how I want to

00:15:52.059 --> 00:15:53.859
lay out my website.

00:15:53.859 --> 00:15:54.859
Let's give it a title.

00:15:54.859 --> 00:16:00.219
I'll call it Korto, and I'm going to create a navigation bar, and on the left side of

00:16:00.219 --> 00:16:06.739
the navigation bar, I'm going to link to the two documents I have, the index.qmd I just

00:16:06.739 --> 00:16:13.859
created, and the hello.qmd that I had renamed from that original R Markdown file.

00:16:13.859 --> 00:16:19.460
The next thing I'm going to do is I like to stay in the RStudio IDE, but I want my build

00:16:19.460 --> 00:16:25.340
tab to be able to get my website going, so I'm just going to restart my project, my RStudio

00:16:25.340 --> 00:16:32.140
project, and I have a build tab that gives me the option to render or preview a website.

00:16:32.140 --> 00:16:41.739
Let's render the website and see what that looks like.

00:16:41.739 --> 00:16:42.739
And there we go.

00:16:42.739 --> 00:16:49.059
We have a website with multiple pages in it that we have very clearly written out in this

00:16:49.059 --> 00:16:51.900
simple and expressive YAML file.

00:16:51.900 --> 00:16:55.380
To me, this is incredibly encouraging.

00:16:56.380 --> 00:16:57.380
Woo-hoo!

00:16:57.380 --> 00:17:08.060
Next, what I'm going to do is I'm going to start setting things up for Julie, and also

00:17:08.060 --> 00:17:09.579
try to be kind to myself.

00:17:09.579 --> 00:17:15.060
I have lots of computation in that hello.qmd, let's assume, and I don't want this to constantly

00:17:15.060 --> 00:17:19.979
keep running every time I update things, so I'm going to set the freeze feature to true,

00:17:19.979 --> 00:17:26.219
which says only rerun the computation when I explicitly ask you to do so in that document,

00:17:26.219 --> 00:17:29.859
otherwise, as I change other things, don't rerun the computation.

00:17:29.859 --> 00:17:35.420
You can see that when I set this, I get this freeze folder where the results of my computation

00:17:35.420 --> 00:17:41.260
is stored, and I can set freeze to be other values, like automatic, where it would only

00:17:41.260 --> 00:17:43.660
update if you actually touch that file.

00:17:43.660 --> 00:17:48.979
I'm going to set it equal to true so that let's see if Julie can later recreate this

00:17:48.979 --> 00:17:52.060
website in a non-R environment.

00:17:52.060 --> 00:17:57.219
So I have a website, I have stored my computations, I have multiple pages.

00:17:57.219 --> 00:17:58.219
What next?

00:17:58.219 --> 00:18:12.219
Yeah, we should be able to publish it.

00:18:13.219 --> 00:18:15.500
All right.

00:18:15.500 --> 00:18:25.180
Well, we could with one command, corto.publish in the terminal actually publish this to CortoPub.

00:18:25.180 --> 00:18:30.020
So if you do want to see the published website, I'm not sure why the video is hanging, but

00:18:30.020 --> 00:18:40.300
if you do want to see the published website, you could go to mine.corto.pub and the website

00:18:40.300 --> 00:18:41.300
is there.

00:18:41.300 --> 00:18:43.459
So this is one of the pages that we created.

00:18:43.459 --> 00:18:47.420
And we're able to do that without, you know, setting up things like actions to run our

00:18:47.420 --> 00:18:50.540
code and whatnot with one line from the terminal.

00:18:50.540 --> 00:18:52.420
All right.

00:18:52.420 --> 00:18:55.500
So what did we see here?

00:18:55.500 --> 00:19:00.260
Now that you've all had a chance to kind of see Corto in action, you might be wondering

00:19:00.260 --> 00:19:05.219
how are R Markdown and Corto different, especially because we were able to just get things going

00:19:05.219 --> 00:19:07.180
by renaming that file.

00:19:07.180 --> 00:19:12.599
The main difference is that with R Markdown, it is the R package R Markdown that does the

00:19:12.599 --> 00:19:18.660
heavy lifting of what needs to happen to go from the RMD file to your output.

00:19:18.660 --> 00:19:22.180
And that's something we as R users are very accustomed to.

00:19:22.180 --> 00:19:27.339
You want to solve a problem, install that package, the package that solves the problem

00:19:27.339 --> 00:19:28.819
you want to solve.

00:19:28.819 --> 00:19:32.500
With Corto, on the other hand, it's the Corto command line interface.

00:19:32.500 --> 00:19:34.859
So not an R package, but a command line interface.

00:19:34.859 --> 00:19:40.819
Something like Git, for example, that's actually doing the heavy lifting of taking your input

00:19:40.819 --> 00:19:47.400
file, running your executable code chunks through either Knitter or Jupyter, creating

00:19:47.400 --> 00:19:55.859
a plain text Markdown file that then uses Pandoc to get to the output of your choice.

00:19:55.859 --> 00:20:01.979
So this is technically pretty impressive, but I'm going to be very honest with you.

00:20:01.979 --> 00:20:05.619
It's not exactly what sparked my interest about Corto.

00:20:05.619 --> 00:20:12.219
What did spark my interest about Corto was how easy it makes it to move between various

00:20:12.219 --> 00:20:13.219
formats.

00:20:13.219 --> 00:20:18.660
So as an educator, the things that are of utmost importance to me is that the artifacts

00:20:18.660 --> 00:20:24.219
I create are reproducible and that there's an ease of transition between various output

00:20:24.219 --> 00:20:25.560
formats.

00:20:25.560 --> 00:20:31.819
At the risk of sounding like a broken record, I do actually have to relay the same information

00:20:31.819 --> 00:20:39.000
to my students in slides as kind of lecture notes in a homework assignment posted on the

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:40.380
course website.

00:20:40.380 --> 00:20:45.560
So oftentimes I'm moving the same content around these different formats.

00:20:45.560 --> 00:20:50.939
And over the last year of doing this with Corto, I felt like I finally found the tool

00:20:50.939 --> 00:20:58.699
that allows me to do this easily without futzing around with my code and the content part of

00:20:58.699 --> 00:21:02.699
my document, but just changing a couple things in the YAML.

00:21:02.699 --> 00:21:09.099
For example, if I want a lesson, kind of a single document as lecture notes or something,

00:21:09.099 --> 00:21:11.140
I can say format HTML.

00:21:11.140 --> 00:21:15.939
I can easily change that to reveal JS without touching anything else in my document, and

00:21:15.939 --> 00:21:17.300
I have a slide deck.

00:21:17.300 --> 00:21:24.979
I can simply call that file in a Corto YAML file to create a website.

00:21:24.979 --> 00:21:31.380
And you can see that all I needed to change is just this YAML.

00:21:31.380 --> 00:21:33.300
I didn't have to remove slide breaks.

00:21:33.300 --> 00:21:36.079
I didn't have to relevel headers.

00:21:36.079 --> 00:21:40.979
That does save me some time, and that time can go to actually focus on the content that

00:21:40.979 --> 00:21:46.420
I'm developing, and that I find extremely liberating.

00:21:46.420 --> 00:21:55.660
But ultimately, while easily creating documents in multiple formats is nice, for the sharing

00:21:55.660 --> 00:22:00.859
story to be complete, the tool needs to support easily sharing things as well.

00:22:00.859 --> 00:22:05.660
So something like that Corto publish command that you can run in the terminal, and I'm

00:22:05.660 --> 00:22:08.920
sure soon a button in the RStudio IDE.

00:22:08.920 --> 00:22:14.380
I think that tooling that makes it easy to share what you do with the world on the web

00:22:14.380 --> 00:22:16.619
is incredibly useful.

00:22:16.619 --> 00:22:22.060
And it's not just useful to you, but to the world, as it facilitates open sharing of knowledge

00:22:22.060 --> 00:22:25.579
for learning and reuse.

00:22:25.579 --> 00:22:31.859
I've been talking about me and my work so far, but I, like many of you, don't operate

00:22:31.859 --> 00:22:35.319
in a silo disconnected from others.

00:22:35.319 --> 00:22:38.819
Much of my work and much of Julie's work is collaborative.

00:22:38.819 --> 00:22:42.619
So over to you, Julie, for collaborating with Corto.

00:22:42.619 --> 00:22:45.020
Thanks, Mina.

00:22:45.020 --> 00:22:50.380
I have gained so much from the open sharing and the web-first approach from the R community,

00:22:50.380 --> 00:22:56.140
and it has so informed the way that I collaborate and the way that I work.

00:22:56.140 --> 00:23:01.420
So I work at the intersection of actionable environmental science, open science, and data

00:23:01.420 --> 00:23:07.699
science, and what I absolutely love doing is mentoring, teaching, and empowering communities,

00:23:07.699 --> 00:23:10.579
having learned from so many of you, like I said.

00:23:10.579 --> 00:23:16.260
And I wanted to pay this forward and welcome more folks to this experience that I've had

00:23:16.260 --> 00:23:19.540
with the R and Mozilla communities in particular.

00:23:19.540 --> 00:23:24.020
So I've made this my job through Openscapes.

00:23:24.020 --> 00:23:28.739
Openscapes is an approach and a movement that I launched in 2018 and have built together

00:23:28.739 --> 00:23:31.359
with my partner, Aaron Robinson.

00:23:31.359 --> 00:23:35.660
Our flagship activity is mentoring research teams in open science.

00:23:35.660 --> 00:23:41.579
We think of open science as a beautiful landscape full of open source software, data, and communities

00:23:41.579 --> 00:23:44.900
and many paths forward.

00:23:44.900 --> 00:23:50.300
And we help people move from the sad, lonely animals in the foreground on the bottom left

00:23:50.300 --> 00:23:55.020
and towards this landscape so that they can explore this and navigate this safely with

00:23:55.020 --> 00:23:56.660
their teams.

00:23:56.660 --> 00:24:02.260
And our role is to welcome folks at the trailhead and help them establish what that trailhead

00:24:02.260 --> 00:24:03.619
even looks like.

00:24:03.619 --> 00:24:04.619
Who's there?

00:24:04.619 --> 00:24:05.680
Who is part of the team?

00:24:05.680 --> 00:24:10.540
How can we think about who can be included and start this journey together with limited

00:24:10.540 --> 00:24:14.140
trampling and frustration?

00:24:14.140 --> 00:24:19.140
So we work with professional research groups in government, academia, and nonprofits, and

00:24:19.140 --> 00:24:24.459
we help these teams modernize their workflows and shift their culture with their teams and

00:24:24.459 --> 00:24:29.339
within their organizations through open source software and open source practices.

00:24:29.859 --> 00:24:35.819
Adrian Rios from NOAA fisheries has been part of Openscapes, and she describes this in this

00:24:35.819 --> 00:24:37.260
way.

00:24:37.260 --> 00:24:41.900
She says as fisheries scientists, we know that when we're in rough seas, it's important

00:24:41.900 --> 00:24:45.300
to keep the fish afloat.

00:24:45.300 --> 00:24:50.459
It's also important to keep the ship afloat and to get out of the storm.

00:24:50.459 --> 00:24:56.020
She says Openscapes helps teams steer out of the storm of email chains with 37 versions

00:24:56.020 --> 00:25:01.900
of the same spreadsheet and into the calmer waters of open science and meaningful collaboration

00:25:01.900 --> 00:25:04.619
using tools like R.

00:25:04.619 --> 00:25:07.020
So I think that I have the best job.

00:25:07.020 --> 00:25:12.060
I get to mentor and collaborate with teams like Audion's who are doing really critical

00:25:12.060 --> 00:25:16.579
and hard work around environment and climate.

00:25:16.579 --> 00:25:21.420
And I get to help them do it a little better by connecting them to the open source tools

00:25:21.420 --> 00:25:25.420
and community resources that we all produce.

00:25:25.420 --> 00:25:29.939
And it really blends working with these teams really blends for me the role of mentoring

00:25:29.939 --> 00:25:34.459
and collaborating because I learn so much along the way.

00:25:34.459 --> 00:25:43.500
And this is definitely true with our story with NASA.

00:25:43.500 --> 00:25:48.579
With NASA, you probably think about outer space, but they collect an unbelievable amount

00:25:48.579 --> 00:25:50.540
of data about earth.

00:25:50.540 --> 00:25:56.020
And researchers use earth data in many ways, including how to understand impacts of the

00:25:56.020 --> 00:26:00.619
heat waves and the wildfires that we're increasingly seeing through the summers due to climate

00:26:00.619 --> 00:26:01.979
change.

00:26:01.979 --> 00:26:07.420
These data are freely available from 12 different data centers across NASA, but researchers

00:26:07.420 --> 00:26:12.619
have to download these data locally from each of these data centers to analyze it locally,

00:26:12.619 --> 00:26:15.420
and this puts a huge burden on the researchers.

00:26:15.420 --> 00:26:21.099
So now, following many years of preparation, these data are migrating to the cloud through

00:26:21.099 --> 00:26:27.180
AWS and others, and NASA data centers will be supporting researchers who will be migrating

00:26:27.180 --> 00:26:31.660
their analytical workflows to the cloud, too.

00:26:31.660 --> 00:26:36.619
So my partner Erin had ten years of experience working with the NASA earth data community,

00:26:36.619 --> 00:26:42.500
and she brought NASA and OpenScapes together in a three-year project that we leared together.

00:26:42.500 --> 00:26:47.979
And our focus is on developing, first and foremost, a mentor community across those

00:26:47.979 --> 00:26:54.900
12 data centers so that they can co-create and teach common tutorials for these researchers

00:26:54.900 --> 00:26:58.219
using NASA earth data.

00:26:58.219 --> 00:27:03.660
So let me just stop here and say that this is a big project, and it is awesome.

00:27:03.660 --> 00:27:07.020
But it was also incredibly intimidating to me.

00:27:07.020 --> 00:27:09.180
I do not know the NASA community.

00:27:09.180 --> 00:27:12.979
This is an organization I've looked up to my whole life.

00:27:12.979 --> 00:27:17.900
I'm not familiar with these types of huge spatial data that they're working with, the

00:27:17.900 --> 00:27:22.699
type of research questions earth scientists are asking and modeling, not to mention cloud

00:27:22.699 --> 00:27:26.540
infrastructure, which is a whole new era.

00:27:26.540 --> 00:27:31.339
But an additional thing that was particularly intimidating to me as an R person is that

00:27:31.339 --> 00:27:35.020
many earth scientists use Python.

00:27:35.020 --> 00:27:38.859
And they are developing tutorials primarily in Jupyter notebooks.

00:27:38.859 --> 00:27:44.099
And my role in leading NASA OpenScapes was not to learn Python from the ground up, but

00:27:44.099 --> 00:27:49.500
I needed to be able to collaborate and interoperate and support Python users.

00:27:49.500 --> 00:27:55.099
So something really powerful, though, is that I brought almost a decade of experience and

00:27:55.099 --> 00:27:57.420
confidence using R Markdown.

00:27:57.420 --> 00:28:02.180
And I've been able to you've probably heard me talk about this, because I talk about it

00:28:02.180 --> 00:28:03.180
a lot.

00:28:03.180 --> 00:28:06.140
I feel like it's a superpower.

00:28:06.380 --> 00:28:10.459
Quarto let me bring this superpower to Python.

00:28:10.459 --> 00:28:12.819
Quarto was emerging right when we needed it.

00:28:12.819 --> 00:28:17.500
And I asked JJ if we could use Quarto for NASA OpenScapes.

00:28:17.500 --> 00:28:22.619
It was really early in its development, and this became a really exciting collaboration

00:28:22.619 --> 00:28:26.260
between the Quarto development team and the NASA mentors.

00:28:26.260 --> 00:28:32.380
This was a really generous and gracious group of people together as we were learning how

00:28:32.380 --> 00:28:37.219
to collaborate together and build tutorials and try new software.

00:28:37.219 --> 00:28:43.380
And we were able to, through our questions and use, influence some of the design features,

00:28:43.380 --> 00:28:48.979
particularly the freeze feature and how it operates with Jupyter notebooks.

00:28:48.979 --> 00:28:54.719
So this is the first Quarto site we developed for our first teaching event last fall.

00:28:54.719 --> 00:28:59.260
This is where we really found traction as a mentor community, and we were able to make

00:28:59.260 --> 00:29:04.060
this beautiful collection of tutorials that was, first of all, helpful for our own development

00:29:04.060 --> 00:29:08.180
as we were learning to collaborate with each other, because we could see which tutorials

00:29:08.180 --> 00:29:10.900
were there already and where the gaps were.

00:29:10.900 --> 00:29:16.579
But it was also a very friendly, contained place for our learners to navigate through

00:29:16.579 --> 00:29:18.939
these resources.

00:29:18.939 --> 00:29:24.579
And importantly, Quarto was also something that we were all able to learn together.

00:29:24.579 --> 00:29:27.979
And that turned out to be really important, because it turned out I wasn't the only person

00:29:27.979 --> 00:29:32.780
who was intimidated by all these moving pieces on all these new pieces of software and how

00:29:32.780 --> 00:29:34.619
to collaborate together.

00:29:34.619 --> 00:29:39.739
Learning Quarto together opened the door for us to talk more about our workflows and develop

00:29:39.739 --> 00:29:44.140
better systems for collaborating and really take this to the next level.

00:29:44.140 --> 00:29:48.920
And from all of our investment and workflows, we were then able to rapidly create additional

00:29:48.920 --> 00:29:52.939
resources for the other teaching workshops that we were leading that were designed to

00:29:52.939 --> 00:29:58.219
meet those learners where they were and interoperate between the materials we developed.

00:29:58.219 --> 00:30:00.579
So there's two things to highlight here.

00:30:00.579 --> 00:30:04.859
The first is that Quarto enables collaborating across coding languages.

00:30:04.859 --> 00:30:07.459
This is one peak of a way to think about this.

00:30:07.459 --> 00:30:11.719
This is a simplified view of one of our YAML files, where you can see we've got multiple

00:30:11.719 --> 00:30:13.459
file types here.

00:30:13.459 --> 00:30:18.060
These are mostly we've mostly focused on Ipy and B, Jupyter Notebook files in our primary

00:30:18.060 --> 00:30:19.819
development so far.

00:30:19.819 --> 00:30:24.500
But as we've worked more and more with the NASA research community, we've discovered

00:30:24.500 --> 00:30:30.300
or that's not the right word, we've found that there is a substantial R community using

00:30:30.300 --> 00:30:31.939
NASA Earth Data Cloud.

00:30:31.939 --> 00:30:36.579
And it's really exciting that the workflow we've invested in and have developed together,

00:30:36.579 --> 00:30:40.020
we can use to support our users as well.

00:30:40.020 --> 00:30:44.699
The second is that Quarto enables contributing from our current tools.

00:30:44.699 --> 00:30:50.839
So some of our team, mainly me and Aaron, used RStudio primarily.

00:30:50.839 --> 00:30:53.780
Some used JupyterLab, VS Code.

00:30:53.780 --> 00:30:58.660
Some edit directly in GitHub through the editor.

00:30:58.660 --> 00:31:02.420
And this was really important that we were all able to use our own tools, because with

00:31:02.420 --> 00:31:08.099
all these moving pieces, we were able to integrate that workflow into the comfort of our own

00:31:08.099 --> 00:31:09.099
tools.

00:31:09.099 --> 00:31:18.219
So let me show you what Quarto looks like in Jupyter Notebooks.

00:31:18.219 --> 00:31:23.239
So this is a Jupyter Notebook, and it's actually running in our Jupyter hub.

00:31:23.239 --> 00:31:27.219
You can see we're going to interoperate with Quarto in the terminal here on the right,

00:31:27.219 --> 00:31:30.859
and we've got all the files that Mina just created on the left.

00:31:30.859 --> 00:31:36.699
So the first thing we'll do is we'll say Quarto preview.

00:31:36.699 --> 00:31:44.099
And this will provide a URL where we can review the previewed version of the site that

00:31:44.099 --> 00:31:45.739
Mina has created.

00:31:45.739 --> 00:31:48.780
So I don't have R installed here.

00:31:48.780 --> 00:31:55.300
But with the freeze function, I'm able to open this in this new environment.

00:31:55.300 --> 00:31:56.819
So here is our beautiful website.

00:31:56.819 --> 00:32:00.359
I like to kind of have them side by side so I can see them refreshed.

00:32:00.359 --> 00:32:04.380
And if we want to add a Jupyter Notebook, let's say, oh, look, I just added one.

00:32:04.380 --> 00:32:05.380
Great.

00:32:05.380 --> 00:32:09.020
I got it.

00:32:09.020 --> 00:32:14.780
So this is a Jupyter Notebook I've got over here on this tab.

00:32:14.780 --> 00:32:17.979
And this is how we can think about Quarto.

00:32:17.979 --> 00:32:23.500
We've got our YAML at the top where we're going to say hello to Quarto penguins in Python.

00:32:23.500 --> 00:32:28.099
We've got our markdown text here, and we're going to use the Palmer penguins package in

00:32:28.099 --> 00:32:29.180
Python.

00:32:29.180 --> 00:32:32.300
This is how it will load the packages.

00:32:32.300 --> 00:32:36.780
And the way you operate this in a Jupyter Notebook is that you execute the code as you

00:32:36.780 --> 00:32:37.780
go.

00:32:37.780 --> 00:32:43.420
So when I press this play button, this is going to execute that code and actually embed

00:32:43.420 --> 00:32:45.900
it in the document.

00:32:45.900 --> 00:32:52.540
So we'll do that again with a plot about penguins by clicking this button.

00:32:52.540 --> 00:32:57.180
And now this plot is here as part of the document.

00:32:57.180 --> 00:33:01.900
So the workflow here is that you execute the code as you go and as you develop, and then

00:33:01.900 --> 00:33:03.619
you save your file as you go.

00:33:03.619 --> 00:33:08.300
So this is the workflow in a Jupyter Notebook.

00:33:08.300 --> 00:33:13.800
And when we save that, now we can think about adding this to our Quarto YAML.

00:33:13.800 --> 00:33:17.819
And the way we do that is exactly the way that Mina did before.

00:33:17.819 --> 00:33:29.099
I can add a Jupyter Notebook right here next to these Quarto files.

00:33:29.099 --> 00:33:34.420
And when we save this YAML file, we're able to peek at the terminal that's going to tell

00:33:34.420 --> 00:33:41.979
us when the site refreshes, and there is indeed our hello Quarto in Python.

00:33:41.979 --> 00:33:49.939
You can see it's beautiful, and it looks exactly the same as the QMD documents in R.

00:33:49.939 --> 00:33:57.439
So let's play around a little bit more, and I'll show you two more things in Quarto.

00:33:57.439 --> 00:34:05.400
So if we wanted to add a figure caption to this plot, we would use the same hash pipe

00:34:05.400 --> 00:34:09.919
comment system that Mina just introduced.

00:34:09.919 --> 00:34:15.520
So I can put this figure caption here, and again, I can execute and save, and this when

00:34:15.520 --> 00:34:23.879
I refresh over here, this will show up in our document.

00:34:23.879 --> 00:34:29.560
And there is our figure caption.

00:34:29.560 --> 00:34:31.000
But you can see that it's not here.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:33.080
It doesn't do anything to the Jupyter Notebook.

00:34:33.080 --> 00:34:35.879
It's a comment in the Jupyter ecosystem.

00:34:35.879 --> 00:34:39.459
It's not affecting the Jupyter Notebook at all.

00:34:39.459 --> 00:34:42.360
Let's add one other feature here in the comment.

00:34:42.360 --> 00:34:50.560
Sorry, in the code chunk option.

00:34:50.560 --> 00:34:55.399
Let's say we wanted to display this plot in the margin instead.

00:34:55.399 --> 00:35:01.399
This is a style that's quite popular.

00:35:01.399 --> 00:35:09.760
So I might have to make this a little bit wider so we can have a look.

00:35:09.760 --> 00:35:10.959
Little bit wider.

00:35:10.959 --> 00:35:11.959
Okay.

00:35:11.959 --> 00:35:17.159
There is our plot in the margin from a Jupyter Notebook.

00:35:17.159 --> 00:35:29.280
Woo!

00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:34.360
So let's now say that operating between formats is really important, particularly when we're

00:35:34.360 --> 00:35:35.600
in collaborating.

00:35:35.600 --> 00:35:41.719
So a workflow that's been really powerful is to convert Jupyter Notebooks into Quarto

00:35:41.719 --> 00:35:48.320
documents so that checking them in with GitHub can reduce merge conflicts.

00:35:48.320 --> 00:35:54.840
So what I can do here is to say Quarto convert and tell it the file, and it will by default

00:35:54.840 --> 00:36:00.080
turn it into a QMD, and you can go back and forth between these formats.

00:36:00.080 --> 00:36:05.600
So you can see it's created a new QMD document, and when I open it in the editor here, this

00:36:05.600 --> 00:36:11.679
is now that same document with our familiar view in QMD form, and you can see the Python.

00:36:11.679 --> 00:36:22.760
So this has a lot of utility and power, and it's very important for teaching as well.

00:36:22.760 --> 00:36:26.199
So Mina, I'll turn it over to you for teaching.

00:36:26.199 --> 00:36:27.199
Thank you.

00:36:27.199 --> 00:36:32.840
So over the last decade, I have thoroughly enjoyed teaching with R Markdown.

00:36:32.840 --> 00:36:37.320
When you get students in the class for the first time and you give them a fully functional

00:36:37.320 --> 00:36:43.439
R Markdown document and ask them to hit knit, and they can see their text and their code

00:36:43.439 --> 00:36:47.560
and the output come together before they even learn any programming.

00:36:47.560 --> 00:36:50.800
You can almost hear, wow, that's so cool in the classroom.

00:36:50.800 --> 00:36:55.879
And I've also loved that this tool is something you can introduce to introductory students

00:36:55.879 --> 00:37:00.560
on the first day of class and that it can grow with them.

00:37:00.560 --> 00:37:09.679
However, as students' expertise grow in statistics and also in computing, and also their needs

00:37:09.679 --> 00:37:14.879
grow in terms of the different outputs they need to produce to, say, just a single homework

00:37:14.879 --> 00:37:21.399
document that they can turn in as an HTML to a well-formatted journal article or a thesis

00:37:21.399 --> 00:37:27.000
that meets the school style, there is a little bit of friction that happens.

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:33.320
And a pleasant surprise, for me this was a pleasant surprise with Corto has been that

00:37:33.320 --> 00:37:37.439
this leveling up has been a lot smoother.

00:37:37.439 --> 00:37:42.520
The learning curve for going from a single document to a multi-document project has been

00:37:42.520 --> 00:37:43.520
a lot smoother.

00:37:43.520 --> 00:37:45.879
So I'll tell the story of one of my students.

00:37:45.879 --> 00:37:47.159
So this is Holland Stam.

00:37:47.159 --> 00:37:53.040
She's an art, history, and visual media studies student who I met when she was taking my regression

00:37:53.040 --> 00:37:55.120
course just last spring.

00:37:55.120 --> 00:38:01.080
Holland came to my class with just one semester of intradata science under her belt, where

00:38:01.080 --> 00:38:02.800
she had learned R Markdown.

00:38:02.800 --> 00:38:08.120
And in my class, we dropped these students into learning Corto after a brief overview

00:38:08.120 --> 00:38:11.080
of how it's different than R Markdown.

00:38:11.080 --> 00:38:15.719
And so she was doing her homework assignments and stuff as single documents in R Markdown,

00:38:15.719 --> 00:38:20.560
but at the same time working on her art history thesis, which was pretty quantitative.

00:38:20.560 --> 00:38:27.439
So if you've ever taken an art history class, you might be familiar with these two textbooks,

00:38:27.439 --> 00:38:32.239
Garner's Art Through the Ages and Jansen's History of Art.

00:38:32.239 --> 00:38:37.199
These are foundational art history textbooks that have been around for decades at this

00:38:37.199 --> 00:38:39.439
point with multiple editions.

00:38:39.439 --> 00:38:46.000
And what Holland was looking for is representation of different genders and ethnicities of artists

00:38:46.159 --> 00:38:51.360
and how much space is given to them in these textbooks and how this changes over, how,

00:38:51.360 --> 00:38:54.159
if at all, this has changed throughout the editions.

00:38:54.159 --> 00:38:56.840
You can see her meticulously measuring in this picture.

00:38:56.840 --> 00:39:00.199
This is exactly what she did to collect her data.

00:39:00.199 --> 00:39:05.000
Actually measure the art that is featured in the textbooks through the editions and

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:10.280
then join this information with demographic data on the artists so that we could analyze

00:39:10.280 --> 00:39:15.120
and kind of try to build a model to see if things have changed over the years, what representation

00:39:15.120 --> 00:39:17.040
looks like.

00:39:17.040 --> 00:39:21.959
On the sad side, the representation was exactly what you would imagine, the lack thereof.

00:39:21.959 --> 00:39:27.719
But on the happy side of this story, as she was working on her thesis, she realized each

00:39:27.719 --> 00:39:32.760
of my chapters could be just like one of my homework files because ultimately what do

00:39:32.760 --> 00:39:34.360
we do in our homework?

00:39:34.360 --> 00:39:38.239
Write a bit of code, get some results out, interpret it, and that's exactly what she

00:39:38.239 --> 00:39:39.639
was doing.

00:39:39.639 --> 00:39:44.020
And then with a bit of Googling around and a little bit of help from me, she was able

00:39:44.020 --> 00:39:49.979
to bring these chapters together with a single YAML file and, you know, turned it into her

00:39:49.979 --> 00:39:50.979
thesis.

00:39:50.979 --> 00:39:55.139
Now, this wasn't without friction, right?

00:39:55.139 --> 00:39:59.020
This sort of kind of leveling up for is not easy.

00:39:59.020 --> 00:40:04.959
However, when she realized that she can add captions to her figures as she creates them

00:40:04.959 --> 00:40:13.139
in the code chunks and that she can, she does not have to manually style citations, millions

00:40:13.139 --> 00:40:18.300
of citations she had for this thesis project that she can just use the visual editor to

00:40:18.300 --> 00:40:20.060
insert these citations.

00:40:20.060 --> 00:40:25.139
She decided, I am willing to put in the effort to do that.

00:40:25.139 --> 00:40:32.500
So as a side story, Holland was in my kind of research lab and she also worked with another

00:40:32.500 --> 00:40:36.320
student of mine, Sarah Lemus, and they packaged up this data.

00:40:36.320 --> 00:40:41.459
So Sarah was incredibly inspired by Holland's enthusiasm about this project and Sarah is

00:40:41.459 --> 00:40:47.300
a stats student who had been working with me over that semester to learn a little bit

00:40:47.300 --> 00:40:51.719
of package development by updating some of the data packages I maintained.

00:40:51.719 --> 00:40:56.760
So it was very clear to us that the enthusiasm between these two students, they should come

00:40:56.760 --> 00:40:59.020
together and work on this project together.

00:40:59.020 --> 00:41:04.300
So if you're interested in the data that Holland collected and Sarah and Holland put together,

00:41:04.300 --> 00:41:06.500
you can actually get this package off grant now.

00:41:06.500 --> 00:41:10.139
It's called Art History and has a really cute hex.

00:41:10.139 --> 00:41:12.139
All right.

00:41:12.139 --> 00:41:19.139
So just like Holland, Korto has solved a lot of my problems as an instructor as well.

00:41:19.139 --> 00:41:23.060
So I am going to demo a few of those to you.

00:41:23.060 --> 00:41:28.780
Now first and foremost, you can open a Korto document in the RStudio IDE and render it.

00:41:28.780 --> 00:41:30.379
I've shown you this before.

00:41:30.379 --> 00:41:31.780
Why am I saying it again?

00:41:31.780 --> 00:41:33.760
I did not have to install anything.

00:41:33.760 --> 00:41:34.760
Everything comes bundled.

00:41:34.760 --> 00:41:40.159
So if you are teaching in the RStudio IDE, no installation required and we can basically

00:41:40.159 --> 00:41:41.159
get going.

00:41:41.159 --> 00:41:43.600
And I think to me that's incredibly liberating.

00:41:43.600 --> 00:41:47.600
Beyond that, though, there's really handy features.

00:41:47.600 --> 00:41:53.800
For example, with a single YAML field code link set to true, I can each of the documents

00:41:53.800 --> 00:41:58.719
that I create can now look a little bit like package documentation you may have seen where

00:41:58.719 --> 00:42:04.639
the functions are clickable and it takes you directly to the documentation for that

00:42:04.639 --> 00:42:05.800
function.

00:42:05.800 --> 00:42:11.239
And that is incredibly helpful for learning and teaching because it saves me a lot of

00:42:11.239 --> 00:42:14.399
time from adding those links.

00:42:14.399 --> 00:42:17.600
Now on the learning side, let's try to make a mistake.

00:42:17.600 --> 00:42:20.000
And let's see that it's really hard.

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:22.479
I want to write false in capital letters.

00:42:22.479 --> 00:42:24.000
I'm trying to make a mistake.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:26.840
Korto is constantly telling me don't do it, Mina.

00:42:26.840 --> 00:42:31.239
So let's go ahead and think that I actually managed to do that.

00:42:31.239 --> 00:42:33.560
And let's render this document.

00:42:33.560 --> 00:42:39.040
The error that we get is human readable and it tells me exactly what to do.

00:42:39.040 --> 00:42:43.959
It says maybe you should try false in small letters instead.

00:42:43.959 --> 00:42:49.919
And this is incredibly helpful for new learners and also experts who might be frustrated reading

00:42:49.919 --> 00:42:55.360
through cryptic YAML errors and really kind of pushes you in the right direction to get

00:42:55.360 --> 00:43:01.800
things going so that, again, you can focus on your content and not the minutia in a way.

00:43:01.800 --> 00:43:06.760
Now, as I said, as an educator, a lot of slide decks is kind of like my life.

00:43:06.760 --> 00:43:12.280
So let's turn this into a Reveal.js presentation again and let me show you a few of the handy

00:43:12.280 --> 00:43:15.159
features here that I use regularly.

00:43:15.159 --> 00:43:19.919
The fact that you get a document outlined by default is really nice if somebody loses

00:43:19.919 --> 00:43:21.879
their place.

00:43:21.879 --> 00:43:24.760
Everyone always asks, can I get a PDF of the slides?

00:43:24.760 --> 00:43:29.479
Now they can without you having to do anything extra.

00:43:29.479 --> 00:43:34.159
Other things that are really handy is being able to annotate your slides.

00:43:34.159 --> 00:43:39.919
So we can turn on the chalkboard feature and this way you can go to something like a plot

00:43:39.919 --> 00:43:42.760
and start outlining things.

00:43:42.760 --> 00:43:46.959
If you, like me, have been an educator through the pandemic, I bet you spent hours in faculty

00:43:46.959 --> 00:43:49.840
meetings, how are we going to show things to students on Zoom?

00:43:49.840 --> 00:43:52.679
Well, this is one way that we can do this.

00:43:52.679 --> 00:43:59.360
We can also open a chalkboard and just start writing on it, which is really handy when

00:43:59.360 --> 00:44:03.919
you're teaching in a classroom where there's a projector screen but nothing else.

00:44:03.919 --> 00:44:08.280
I can also turn on Multiplex, which is the feature we're using right now if you're following

00:44:08.280 --> 00:44:12.600
along, and it will, you know, move forward your slides for you.

00:44:12.600 --> 00:44:17.000
So even if your students fall asleep, they can sort of, you know, stay with you as you

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:18.520
go through things.

00:44:18.520 --> 00:44:23.360
In order to do this, you open the speaker file and kind of present from that and post

00:44:23.360 --> 00:44:27.080
the non-speaker file for them.

00:44:27.080 --> 00:44:33.159
Another thing I'm going to do here is to turn on the code so that it is visible, because

00:44:33.159 --> 00:44:37.360
when I'm teaching, I would like to show the code to my students.

00:44:37.360 --> 00:44:40.280
And let's show one more handy feature.

00:44:40.280 --> 00:44:45.199
Oftentimes when you have a big chunk of code, like a lengthy ggplot code, you may want to

00:44:45.199 --> 00:44:48.439
iterate through that highlighting things line by line.

00:44:48.439 --> 00:44:54.239
So with one chunk option, you can define which lines you want to highlight, and it automatically

00:44:54.239 --> 00:44:58.560
adds animation to your slides so that you can step through them.

00:44:58.560 --> 00:45:02.919
And to me, that's really helpful, because I didn't have to add characters to my code

00:45:02.919 --> 00:45:03.919
to do that.

00:45:03.919 --> 00:45:05.959
Now, my plot is tiny.

00:45:05.959 --> 00:45:09.040
That's not helpful.

00:45:09.040 --> 00:45:14.280
But again, without me having to do extra work to move it on the next slide, I can say change

00:45:14.360 --> 00:45:19.000
the output location to next slide, and it will automatically do that for me without

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:24.040
me referring back to an older chunk label or something like that.

00:45:24.040 --> 00:45:29.479
So again, a lot of these things, many of you might know how to solve, but I think the fact

00:45:29.479 --> 00:45:34.080
that they're solved so elegantly is quite liberating.

00:45:34.080 --> 00:45:38.239
The last thing I'm going to talk about is what about the research side of my life.

00:45:38.239 --> 00:45:44.360
Well, let's open a new project, and let's go ahead and write a paper.

00:45:44.360 --> 00:45:50.199
I'm going to submit a paper to the Journal of American Statistical Association.

00:45:50.199 --> 00:45:56.000
With one comment, I can basically from the terminal use one of the templates that are

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:59.760
available, and there's a growing number of templates there.

00:45:59.760 --> 00:46:00.760
Should I trust the authors?

00:46:00.760 --> 00:46:01.760
What do you guys think?

00:46:01.760 --> 00:46:04.239
Should we trust the core development team?

00:46:04.239 --> 00:46:06.479
I think I'm going to say yeah, okay.

00:46:06.479 --> 00:46:10.479
And I'm going to call this my awesome paper.

00:46:10.479 --> 00:46:15.679
This will generate a template for me that I can author in Corto, which means I can put

00:46:15.679 --> 00:46:21.479
my code and my text in the same document, which is how I generally like to write my

00:46:21.479 --> 00:46:22.959
code.

00:46:22.959 --> 00:46:26.879
And another nice thing here is that, you know, if I was to get rejected from this journal

00:46:26.879 --> 00:46:32.320
and wanted to submit to another one, changing between styles is pretty easy, again, without

00:46:32.320 --> 00:46:35.239
changing your source code.

00:46:35.239 --> 00:46:40.959
So let's go ahead and give it a title, my awesome paper that's ready to be submitted,

00:46:40.959 --> 00:46:45.360
and I'll put my name as first author, and we can render it to a document, and if any

00:46:45.360 --> 00:46:51.360
of you in the audience have used the ASA style before, the output should look pretty familiar

00:46:51.360 --> 00:46:53.360
to you.

00:46:53.360 --> 00:46:55.360
Woo-woo!

00:46:55.479 --> 00:46:57.479
Woo-woo!

00:46:57.479 --> 00:47:04.479
Now, there's unfortunately one drawback.

00:47:04.479 --> 00:47:08.479
Corto does not write your paper for you.

00:47:08.479 --> 00:47:13.479
But my experience with the Corto development team is that when you open issues, they're

00:47:13.479 --> 00:47:17.479
like really quick to respond, so I don't know, maybe by the end of the week they'll figure

00:47:17.479 --> 00:47:20.479
out how to write our papers for us, too.

00:47:20.479 --> 00:47:21.479
All right.

00:47:21.600 --> 00:47:28.600
So we've talked about Corto flattening the learning curve and, you know, basically saying

00:47:28.600 --> 00:47:35.600
that when we are leveling up from a single document to a multi-document input and going

00:47:35.600 --> 00:47:42.600
to various output types, and I said that this was a pleasant surprise to me.

00:47:42.600 --> 00:47:45.600
In hindsight, it should not have been a surprise.

00:47:45.600 --> 00:47:49.600
It's just not what I was thinking when I first started teaching with Corto.

00:47:49.719 --> 00:47:55.719
But if you think about the features of Corto, like consistent citation syntax across various

00:47:55.719 --> 00:48:03.719
formats, more intentional control over when you should run and rerun your computation,

00:48:03.719 --> 00:48:11.719
and a single, minimal, human-readable YAML that controls inputs, layouts, and theming,

00:48:11.719 --> 00:48:18.719
everything in one file, all of these features contribute to flattening that curve for kind

00:48:18.840 --> 00:48:22.840
of creating more complex outputs.

00:48:22.840 --> 00:48:30.840
But beyond just growing and expanding the scope of your work with Corto, I think that

00:48:30.840 --> 00:48:34.840
Corto can grow with learners in a profound way as well.

00:48:34.840 --> 00:48:41.840
The fact that Corto is language and independent and also authoring tool independent offers

00:48:41.840 --> 00:48:46.840
an opportunity for folks to take Corto with them in their data science journey, wherever

00:48:46.959 --> 00:48:49.959
that journey might take them.

00:48:49.959 --> 00:48:57.959
After working on this for a year almost with Julie, I am almost tempted to learn Python.

00:48:57.959 --> 00:48:59.959
And maybe I will.

00:48:59.959 --> 00:49:00.959
But you know what?

00:49:00.959 --> 00:49:03.959
Who is learning Python are my students.

00:49:03.959 --> 00:49:08.959
And they're learning Python and Julia and other languages, mostly in their computer

00:49:08.959 --> 00:49:10.959
science courses.

00:49:11.080 --> 00:49:17.080
And to imagine that they could learn R in RStudio with Corto in my class and then go

00:49:17.080 --> 00:49:22.080
take a computer science class where they're probably living in a Jupyter notebook and

00:49:22.080 --> 00:49:28.080
learning Python but still using Corto, that sounds like an incredibly bright future to

00:49:28.080 --> 00:49:29.080
me.

00:49:29.080 --> 00:49:34.080
And a bright future includes things we can't imagine yet as well.

00:49:34.080 --> 00:49:38.080
So Julie will now tell us a bit about reimagining with Corto.

00:49:38.199 --> 00:49:40.199
Thanks, Meena.

00:49:40.199 --> 00:49:47.199
So we've already seen how much Corto can do for teaching and collaborating and sharing.

00:49:47.199 --> 00:49:50.199
And now I want to push it a bit further.

00:49:50.199 --> 00:49:55.199
What if we could reimagine open science as part of the climate movement?

00:49:55.199 --> 00:49:59.199
We know what this R community and the open science and open source communities are

00:49:59.199 --> 00:50:01.199
capable of.

00:50:01.199 --> 00:50:06.199
So what if we put that energy towards climate?

00:50:06.320 --> 00:50:12.320
Because we're in a climate emergency, we must rapidly and radically reshape society.

00:50:12.320 --> 00:50:16.320
We need every solution and every solver.

00:50:16.320 --> 00:50:17.320
This is hard.

00:50:17.320 --> 00:50:19.320
And it's big.

00:50:19.320 --> 00:50:25.320
And my hope lies in this community and climate researchers and everyone in this

00:50:25.320 --> 00:50:30.320
movement who feels like what they do every single day plays a part.

00:50:30.439 --> 00:50:36.439
So let's think about this concretely with three user groups in this community,

00:50:36.439 --> 00:50:38.439
in this movement.

00:50:38.439 --> 00:50:44.439
First are scientists who are working directly in line with climate change.

00:50:44.439 --> 00:50:50.439
This could be fisheries scientists who are studying where our food sources are

00:50:50.439 --> 00:50:56.439
migrating to as the oceans warm and operating with managers and stakeholders.

00:50:56.439 --> 00:50:59.439
They're working with really hard problems.

00:50:59.560 --> 00:51:01.560
These really hard big problems.

00:51:01.560 --> 00:51:05.560
And they can also feel stuck on the little problems of moving files around

00:51:05.560 --> 00:51:07.560
and interoperating with each other.

00:51:07.560 --> 00:51:13.560
That's really where OpenScapes has been really bringing this passion and this

00:51:13.560 --> 00:51:17.560
movement that we feel in the R community to help these researchers and help

00:51:17.560 --> 00:51:20.560
connect them there.

00:51:20.560 --> 00:51:25.560
And I think now so many of you that I talk to in the open source and R

00:51:25.679 --> 00:51:26.679
communities.

00:51:26.679 --> 00:51:27.679
Okay.

00:51:27.679 --> 00:51:31.679
So the second category is open science and R communities.

00:51:31.679 --> 00:51:34.679
I know a lot of you are feeling stuck, too.

00:51:34.679 --> 00:51:40.679
You're feeling the pressure on climate and feeling like changing to more

00:51:40.679 --> 00:51:42.679
efficient light bulbs isn't enough.

00:51:42.679 --> 00:51:48.679
What if you aligned your daily work as part of climate action as well?

00:51:48.679 --> 00:51:51.679
We want Posit to be around in 100 years.

00:51:51.800 --> 00:51:56.800
What is 100 years going to look like if we don't act now and really put this

00:51:56.800 --> 00:51:58.800
effort together?

00:51:58.800 --> 00:52:04.800
And the third category in theme with the conference is extendable beyond

00:52:04.800 --> 00:52:06.800
these two categories.

00:52:06.800 --> 00:52:12.800
So we really need every solution and every solver across all facets of

00:52:12.800 --> 00:52:19.800
geographies and people and skill level and experience with technology.

00:52:19.919 --> 00:52:21.919
So this work is really hard.

00:52:21.919 --> 00:52:26.919
And we'll return to concrete things that we can do in a moment.

00:52:26.919 --> 00:52:31.919
But this really does mean slowing down a bit in order to speed up.

00:52:31.919 --> 00:52:34.919
But it speeds up like a flywheel.

00:52:34.919 --> 00:52:39.919
My colleague Ileana Fenwick is a marine ecologist who participated in

00:52:39.919 --> 00:52:41.919
OpenScapes earlier last year.

00:52:41.919 --> 00:52:47.919
And she really quickly became a member of the team teaching and extending

00:52:48.040 --> 00:52:52.040
and connecting other communities and seeing what was possible.

00:52:52.040 --> 00:52:56.040
And the way she describes this is beautiful.

00:52:56.040 --> 00:53:00.040
Because of OpenScapes, I've renewed hope in how we can bring about a

00:53:00.040 --> 00:53:02.040
kinder future in science.

00:53:02.040 --> 00:53:06.040
I see a commitment in the open science community to bridging the gaps where

00:53:06.040 --> 00:53:09.040
we've left members of our community behind.

00:53:09.040 --> 00:53:13.040
And it inspires me.

00:53:13.159 --> 00:53:17.159
So we're talking about a profound culture shift that involves real

00:53:17.159 --> 00:53:21.159
deliberate work on both the tech and the human side.

00:53:21.159 --> 00:53:24.159
And we've got the tech side really figured out.

00:53:24.159 --> 00:53:28.159
The momentum and the potential and what we're all doing is amazing and

00:53:28.159 --> 00:53:30.159
phenomenal.

00:53:30.159 --> 00:53:33.159
And we can bring that power and energy to the human side, too.

00:53:33.159 --> 00:53:36.159
We can build inclusion into our daily work.

00:53:36.159 --> 00:53:40.159
So let's think about the teams or the colleagues or the people that you

00:53:40.159 --> 00:53:42.159
interact with.

00:53:42.280 --> 00:53:46.280
And I think that they are probably way more similar to the groups I work

00:53:46.280 --> 00:53:48.280
with than we might expect.

00:53:48.280 --> 00:53:50.280
First of all, it means talking to colleagues.

00:53:50.280 --> 00:53:52.280
Asking them how they're doing.

00:53:52.280 --> 00:53:54.280
Are they stuck?

00:53:54.280 --> 00:53:56.280
What does their workflow look like?

00:53:56.280 --> 00:53:58.280
Where is their friction?

00:53:58.280 --> 00:54:00.280
Who's contributing to our workflow?

00:54:00.280 --> 00:54:04.280
Where are the handoffs maybe between reports or data?

00:54:04.280 --> 00:54:06.280
Where are people feeling friction?

00:54:06.280 --> 00:54:08.280
What can we do to help?

00:54:08.280 --> 00:54:10.280
So this means asking all these questions.

00:54:10.399 --> 00:54:12.399
But really, and that's hard enough.

00:54:12.399 --> 00:54:14.399
Those open-ended questions.

00:54:14.399 --> 00:54:16.399
Another hard part is listening.

00:54:16.399 --> 00:54:18.399
Listening is really hard.

00:54:18.399 --> 00:54:22.399
It means that you are not trying to assume what they need.

00:54:22.399 --> 00:54:26.399
You're not trying to solutioneer as soon as you hear something.

00:54:26.399 --> 00:54:30.399
Because oftentimes, we don't even have language to describe where we're

